SIMPLE: iliac
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Iliac
<hw>Il"i*ac</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Iliacus</ets>, Gr. <?/. See <er>Iliad</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining
to ancient Ilium, or Troy.</def> <rj><au>Gladstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iliac</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Iliac
<hw>Il"i*ac</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>iliaque</ets>. See
<er>Ileum</er>, and cf. <er>Jade</er> a stone.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to, or in the region of, the ilium,
or dorsal bone of the pelvis; <as>as, the <ex>iliac</ex>
artery</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>ileac</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>See <er>Ileac</er>, 1.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Iliac crest</b></col>, <cd>the upper margin of the
ilium.</cd> -- <col><b>Iliac passion</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Ileus</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Iliac region</b></col>, <cd>a region of
the abdomen, on either side of the hypogastric regions, and below the
lumbar regions.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iliacal</ent>⟦br⟧
